Suspected midge gall, is apparently a mite.

"Bud gall caused by Eriophyes lepidosparti (Keifer) (pi. 33)
The mites attack the buds and inhibit elongation of the shoot;
the result is a visible configuration of the affected structure
somewhat similar to a rosette. There is considerable crowding
and bunching together of malformed, stunted, thickened
shoots and aborted buds with short outgrowths.
This wormlike, pinkish mite measures 170-180 microns long.
The featherclaws are 5-rayed; the dorsal shield has numerous
short, weak lines scattered at the middle and enclosed by 2
longitudinal, parallel ridges; the hysterosoma is completely
covered with rounded microtubercles; the coxae are abundantly
granular; and the coverflap of the female genitaha has
14 radiating ribs. This last characteristic is particularly distinctive.
The mites inhabit the buds. They were found in June on
Lepidospartum squamatum, a rigid broomlike shrub common
in washes and gravelly places in California.

Reference: Keifer, 1951: 95."

description: According to Dr Art Shapiro the California Ringlet (Coenonympha tullia california) "is disappearing from the Sacramento Valley and is intolerant of urbanization". So this is a rare observation of this butterfly at Mississippi Bar that is like an Island in an urbanized area next to Lake Natoma.
Where fiddleneck is flowering often the Silvery Blue that are by far the most numerous of the Blues at Mississippi Bar,can be seen feeding in the early spring.
As spring progresses into April Miniature or Dwarf Lupine are seen profusely growing at Mississippi Bar along the trails in the area.

Dove's-foot Crane's-bill are commonly seen all throughout Mississippi Bar.In spring it's not unusual to see all the Typical Blue butterflies in the area feeding on it's pink flowers.Such as the Silvery Blue (Glaucopsyche lygdamus) in the 3rd image feeding on it's flower.
This photo is typical for what I've been seeing with the volume of Blue Dicks seen all around the Missisippi Bar this spring.

The Acmon Blue was observed near Lake Natoma at Mississippi Bar on a beautiful spring like day with temps in the mid-70's.See link below for more info on this butterfly.
http://butterfly.ucdavis.edu/butterfly/Plebejus/acmon
Found at Mississipi Bar near Lake Natoma.

With the exploding numbers of the Pipevine Swallowtails now seen at Mississippi Bar,this Fiddeneck's flower has now become one this butterflies favorite food sources in the area where it is seen growing.

description: The water bird had the body of a duck, with a thick, pointed beak and red eyes. This was the winter plumage, and the white feathers extended to the back of the neck, unlike the other loon species. It swam in the smooth Ocean.
The large, male pinniped had thick, leathery skin and large, paddled feet. He was resting calmly on the surface of the smooth Ocean waters, a beautifully calming sight.

The shells were located in a calm pool, and they were clearly inspected. The shell is a light brown dome, with light rings around the shell. This limpet is less rough, grooved than the other species of the Rocky Shore.

This small fish was darting around the pools with a lot of energy. The body was small, streamlined, and blotched brown/gray. The fins were large relative to the body, at least for a standard ray-finned fish. These swam in the Rocky Shore tide pools.
The black//blue shell with a white top was moving around. The crabs little legs were effortlessly carrying the critter across the pool. It made its home in the Rocky Shore environment.
The shell was nearby a large colony of these mussels. They were ovular, silvery, and dark. This species is the common mussel of the Rocky Shore ecosystems in the region's tide pools.
The large bulk of floating remnants of a kelp forest was a very long tube, with a large, egg-like dome at the end. It was floating in the Rocky Shore tidepool.
Looks to be a Johnson's jumper. Watched it hop from a few leaves on a rose bush and attempt to hop on side of building, but it missed and dropped down to the ground.
